    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid is primarily produced when your muscles use anaerobic respiration during intense exercise, like HIIT, because the oxygen supply can't keep up with energy demand. Instead of fully breaking down glucose with oxygen, cells partially break it down, resulting in lactate as a byproduct. Your body manages this by converting most of the lactate back into pyruvate, which can then be used as fuel in other tissues, or it can be cleared through the breath and kidneys over time.",
      "source": "target",
